\li{Explain what it means}
\li{Connect to user's original question}
\li{Suggest related patterns to explore}
\li{Offer to dive deeper if interested}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Output Formatting}
\p{\strong{For setup instructions}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Command to run
command --with-flags
\stopverb}

\p{Followed by brief explanation and expected output}

\p{\strong{For diagnostic steps}: > \strong{Check}: [what to verify] > \strong{Command}: \code{\startverb command here\stopverb} > \strong{Expected}: [what success looks like] > \strong{If different}: [what to do]}

\p{\strong{For captured traffic explanation}: Use \strong{bold} for field names, \code{\startverb code formatting\stopverb} for values, and clear hierarchical structure:}

\p{\strong{Request structure}:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{model}: \code{\startverb claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{system}: System prompt text...}
\li{\strong{messages}: Array of conversation turns}
\li{\strong{role}: \code{\startverb user\stopverb} or \code{\startverb assistant\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{content}: Message text or tool results}
}

\p{\strong{For reference to bundled docs}: When detailed information exists in reference files, point there: "For complete certificate installation across all platforms, see [reference/setup-installation-certificate.md](reference/setup-installation-certificate.md)."}

\p{\strong{For security-sensitive operations}: > ⚠️ \strong{Security Note}: [Clear explanation of implications]}
}

\subtree{
\title{Usage Guidelines}
\p{To operate effectively as the cc-trace skill:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{ALWAYS use AskUserQuestion tool for questions} - Never ask questions in plain text; use the structured tool interface with clear options}
\li{\strong{Assess context before acting} - Don't assume user's state; ask or verify using AskUserQuestion}
\li{\strong{Verify each step} - Don't proceed until confirmation of success; use AskUserQuestion for verification confirmations}
\li{\strong{Explain technical concepts} - User may be new to proxies/certificates}
\li{\strong{Provide diagnostic commands} - Teach users to troubleshoot independently}
\li{\strong{Balance detail with clarity} - Technical accuracy without overwhelming}
\li{\strong{Reference bundled docs} - Point to detailed guides for deep-dives}
\li{\strong{Emphasize security appropriately} - Clear about risks without being alarmist}
\li{\strong{Teach patterns, not just procedures} - Help users learn to analyze traffic independently}
\li{\strong{Adapt to experience level} - More guidance for beginners, quicker for experts}
\li{\strong{Make success measurable} - Every step has clear verification}
}

\p{Support all three use cases equally:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Learning}: Explain what's being seen and why it matters}
\li{\strong{Debugging}: Systematic diagnosis with actionable fixes}
\li{\strong{Optimization}: Pattern recognition and efficiency analysis}
}

\p{When uncertain about user intent, context, or next step, use the AskUserQuestion tool to gather information rather than assume.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Reference}
\p{This section provides condensed commands and syntax for quick lookup during active use.}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start (For Experienced Users)}
\p{Complete setup sequence for users familiar with mitmproxy:}

\pre{\startverb
# 1. Install mitmproxy
brew install mitmproxy                    # macOS
# apt install mitmproxy                   # Linux (Debian/Ubuntu)
# pip install mitmproxy                   # Alternative (any platform)

# 2. Generate certificate (run and immediately quit)
mitmproxy
# Press 'q' to quit

# 3. Trust certificate (macOS)
sudo security add-trusted-cert -d -p ssl -p basic \
  -k /Library/Keychains/System.keychain \
  ~/.mitmproxy/mitmproxy-ca-cert.pem

# 4. Add proxy_claude function to ~/.zshrc or ~/.bashrc
# See complete function code in Setup Assistance → Step 3 above

# 5. Reload shell configuration
source ~/.zshrc                           # or source ~/.bashrc

# 6. Verify setup (optional but recommended)
bash ~/.claude/skills/cc-trace/scripts/verify-setup.sh

# 7. Start mitmweb (Terminal 1)
# Browser only mode:
mitmweb --web-port 8081 --set flow_filter='~d api.anthropic.com'
# OR with programmatic access (enables CLI analysis):
mitmweb --web-port 8081 --set flow_filter='~d api.anthropic.com' --save-stream-file ~/claude-flows.mitm

# 8. Start Claude Code with proxy (Terminal 2)
proxy_claude

# 9. View traffic in browser
# Navigate to: http://127.0.0.1:8081

# 10. (Optional) Extract slash command expansions programmatically
~/.claude/skills/cc-trace/scripts/show-last-prompt.sh
# Or extract all user messages:
mitmdump -r ~/claude-flows.mitm -s ~/.claude/skills/cc-trace/scripts/extract-slash-commands.py
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Filter Syntax Reference}
\p{Use these filter expressions in mitmweb or mitmproxy CLI:}

\p{\strong{Domain} - ~d - Example: ~d api.anthropic.com - Match domain \strong{URL path} - ~u - Example: ~u /messages - Match URL path \strong{Method} - ~m - Example: ~m POST - Match HTTP method \strong{Status code} - ~c - Example: ~c 200 - Match status code \strong{Request body size} - ~bq - Example: ~bq 1000 - Request body > N bytes \strong{Response body size} - ~bs - Example: ~bs 10000 - Response body > N bytes \strong{Header} - ~h - Example: ~h x-api-key - Match header name \strong{Body text} - ~t - Example: ~t "error" - Search body text \strong{AND operator} - & - Example: ~d api.anthropic.com & ~m POST - Combine filters (AND) \strong{OR operator} - | - Example: ~m POST | ~m GET - Either filter (OR) \strong{NOT operator} - ! - Example: !~c 200 - Negate filter (NOT)}

\p{\strong{Common combinations}:}

\pre{\startverb
~d api.anthropic.com & ~m POST          # Anthropic API POST requests
~d api.anthropic.com & ~u /messages     # Only /messages endpoint
~c 200 & ~bs 50000                      # Successful responses > 50KB
!~c 200                                 # Failed requests (non-200 status)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{CLI Keyboard Shortcuts (mitmproxy)}
\p{For users preferring terminal interface over web UI:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb ↑\stopverb} / \code{\startverb ↓\stopverb} - Navigate flows (up/down)}
\li{\code{\startverb Enter\stopverb} - View flow details}
\li{\code{\startverb Tab\stopverb} - Cycle through Request/Response/Detail tabs}
\li{\code{\startverb q\stopverb} - Back / Quit current view}
\li{\code{\startverb f\stopverb} - Set filter expression}
\li{\code{\startverb C\stopverb} - Clear all flows}
\li{\code{\startverb e\stopverb} - Edit selected flow}
\li{\code{\startverb m\stopverb} - Change view mode (auto, hex, json, etc.)}
\li{\code{\startverb r\stopverb} - Replay request}
\li{\code{\startverb w\stopverb} - Save flows to file}
\li{\code{\startverb ?\stopverb} - Show help / keyboard shortcuts}
}

\p{\strong{Starting mitmproxy CLI}:}

\pre{\startverb
mitmproxy                                # Standard CLI interface
mitmproxy --set flow_filter='~d api.anthropic.com'  # Pre-filtered
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Commands}
\p{\strong{Starting mitmweb (web interface)}:}

\pre{\startverb
mitmweb --web-port 8081                  # Basic start
mitmweb --no-web-open-browser            # Don't auto-open browser
mitmweb --set flow_filter='~d api.anthropic.com'  # Pre-filter
mitmweb --save-stream-file ~/claude-flows.mitm  # Enable programmatic access
mitmweb --listen-port 9090 --web-port 9091  # Custom ports
mitmweb -s script.py                     # Load Python script
mitmweb -r saved-flows.mitm              # Replay saved flows
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Starting mitmdump (headless/logging)}:}

\pre{\startverb
mitmdump -w output.mitm                  # Save all flows to file
mitmdump --set flow_filter='~d api.anthropic.com' -w output.mitm
mitmdump --flow-detail 2                 # Print detailed flow info
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Certificate management (macOS)}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Verify certificate is trusted
security find-certificate -c mitmproxy -a

# Trust certificate
sudo security add-trusted-cert -d -p ssl -p basic \
  -k /Library/Keychains/System.keychain \
  ~/.mitmproxy/mitmproxy-ca-cert.pem

# Remove certificate
sudo security delete-certificate -c mitmproxy /Library/Keychains/System.keychain
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Proxy environment management}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Set proxy (done automatically by proxy_claude function)
export HTTP_PROXY=http://127.0.0.1:8080
export HTTPS_PROXY=http://127.0.0.1:8080
export NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS="$HOME/.mitmproxy/mitmproxy-ca-cert.pem"
export NODE_TLS_REJECT_UNAUTHORIZED=0

# Clear proxy environment
unset HTTP_PROXY HTTPS_PROXY http_proxy https_proxy NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS NODE_TLS_REJECT_UNAUTHORIZED

# Verify proxy is set
echo $HTTP_PROXY
env | grep -i proxy
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Diagnostic commands}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Check if mitmproxy is listening
lsof -i :8080                            # Proxy port
lsof -i :8081                            # Web UI port

# Test proxy with curl
curl -x http://127.0.0.1:8080 http://example.com

# Verify mitmproxy installation
command -v mitmproxy
mitmproxy --version

# Run verification script
bash ~/.claude/skills/cc-trace/scripts/verify-setup.sh
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Parsing streamed responses}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Copy response from mitmweb, then parse with bundled TypeScript parser
pbpaste | npx tsx ~/.claude/skills/cc-trace/scripts/parse-streamed-response.ts
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Programmatic analysis (requires --save-stream-file)}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Show last user prompt (slash command expansion)
~/.claude/skills/cc-trace/scripts/show-last-prompt.sh

# Extract all user messages
mitmdump -r ~/claude-flows.mitm -s ~/.claude/skills/cc-trace/scripts/extract-slash-commands.py

# View all flows
mitmdump -r ~/claude-flows.mitm

# View with detailed info
mitmdump -r ~/claude-flows.mitm --flow-detail 2

# Run custom analysis script
mitmdump -r ~/claude-flows.mitm -s custom-script.py
\stopverb}

\p{For comprehensive programmatic analysis methods, see [reference/usage-programmatic-access.md](reference/usage-programmatic-access.md).}
}
}
}